Table III shows the comparison results of our proposed network and the state-of-the -arts on the VQA 2.0 test split.
The results demonstrates that our GMA mechanism improves the performance over the baseline BUTD [1] by 4.49% in term of the test-std accuracy.
We also compare our model with some excellent attention-based approaches, such as SAN [20], FDA [55], Co-attention [21], RelAtt [56], DCN [57], RAF [58],
and BAN+Glove [4].
In table III, our GMA outperforms these methods in all the metrics, which proves that the proposed Graph Matching Attention mechanism is more effective in the VQA task.
Since our model builds graph structure for both the image and the question representation, we compare our model with the graph-based and tree-based approaches, such as GraphLearner [14], SceneGCN [15], VCTREE-HL [59], which merely built graph on visual modality.
Our GMA method overwhelms these methods, which verifies the cross-modality graph-based representation is feasible.
Finally, we make comparison with state-of-the-art relationship learning methods, including Free_VQA [61],
BLOCK [62],
SEADA [65],
MuRel [25],
Counter [63], and DF [64]. Results shows that our accuracy score on the test-dev split overwhelms these methods.

Table IV shows the results of our network on the GQA test split.
We compare our GMA model with both baselines as well as state-of-the-art methods. The baselines include Local Prior, Global Prior, and CNN+LSTM, which are introduced by GQA dataset [50]. Specifically, based on the question group, the Local and Global Prior models return the most common answer for each group. The CNN+LSTM model is simple fusion approaches between the text and the image.
As we can see in Table IV, the performance of our GMA model is much better than those baselines. In terms of Accuracy metric, our GMA model is 28.33% higher than that of Local Prior model, 25.95% higher than that of Global Prior model, and 10.71% higher than CNN+LSTM model. The results verifies that our method is effective in solving visual question answering task on GQA dataset.
Next, we compare with several attention-based approaches, including BUTD [1] and MAC [38].
Our GMA model exceed the BUTD model by 7.52% and the MAC model by 3.20%, which demonstrate that our graph match attention mechanism is available for cross-modality alignment and can effectively carry out feature fusion between different modalities.
Finally, we compare our GMA model with several state-of-the-art graph-based methods, such as SceneGCN [15], LCGN [53], and GRNs [66]. These methods applied graph message passing strategy and performed relational reasoning. Our model works better than SceneGCN and LCGN in all metrics, with the overall accuracy 2.7% and 1.16% higher than the two, respectively. Besides, the performance of our GMA network is comparable with GRNs [66].
